      <chapter xml:id="intro-groups">
        <title>Intro to Groups</title>
      
        <section xml:id="group-basics">
          <title>Group Basics </title>
      
            <blockquote>
              <p>
                <q>Most great learning happens in groups.</q>
              </p>
              <attribution>Ken Robinson</attribution>
            </blockquote>
      
          <definition xml:id="def-binop">
              <title>Binary Operation</title> 
              <idx><h>binary-operation</h></idx>
      
              <statement>
                <p>
                  A <em>binary operation</em> on a set <m>S</m> is a function
                  <me>
                    -\cdot-:S\times S\to S,\text{given by } (x,y)\to x\cdot y.
                  </me>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>
      
            <remark>
              <p>
                We often write <m>xy</m> instead of <m>x\cdot y</m> for simplicity.
              </p>
            </remark>
      
            <definition xml:id="def-group">
              <title>Group</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  A <em>group</em> is a pair <m>(G, \cdot)</m> where <m>G</m> is a set and <m>\cdot</m> is a <xref text="title" ref="def-binop"/> on <m>G</m>, called <em>group multiplication</em>, satisfying the following properties:
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        (Associativity) for all <m>x,y,z\in G</m> we have <m>(x\cdot y)\cdot z=x\cdot (y\cdot z)</m> 
                      </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        (Identity Element) there exists <m>e\in G</m> such that <m>e·x=x·e=x</m> for all <m>x\in G</m>
                        <notation><usage><m>e</m></usage><description>the identity element of a group</description></notation>          
      
                      </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        (Inverses) for each <m>x\in G</m>, there is an element <m>y\in G</m> such that <m>xy=e=yx</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                  <notation><usage><m>(G,\cdot)</m></usage><description>a group <m>G</m> and its binary operation <m>\cdot</m></description></notation>          
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>
      
            <remark>
              <p>
                Although a group is a pair, we will usually refer to the group by only naming the underlying set, <m>G</m>.
              </p>
            </remark>
      
            <remark>
              <p>
                We say that <q><m>S</m> is closed under the operation <m>\cdot</m></q>, when we want to emphasize that for any <m>x,y\in S</m> the result of the operation, <m>xy</m>, is an element of <m>S</m>. However note that closure is really part of the definition of a binary operation on a set, and it is implicitly assumed whenever we consider such an operation.
              </p>
            </remark>
      
            <theorem xml:id="thm-properties-of-groups">
              <title>Properties of Groups</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p xml:id="part-unique-group-identity">
                        (Unique Identity) In a group <m>G</m>, the element <m>e</m> satisfying the second axiom of <xref ref="def-group" /> is unique, and we thus refer to it as the <em>identity element</em> of <m>G</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
      
                    <li>
                      <p xml:id="part-unique-group-inverse">
                        (Unique Inverses) In a group <m>G</m>, for each <m>x</m>, the element <m>y</m> satisfying the last axiom of <xref ref="def-group" /> is unique, and we thus refer to it as the <em>the inverse</em> of <m>x</m> and we will henceforth denote it by <m>x^{-1}</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
      
                    <li>
                      <p xml:id="part-cancellation">
                        (Cancellation) if <m>xy = xz</m>, then <m>y=z</m>. Similarly, if <m>yx = zx</m>, then <m>y = z</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </statement>
      
              <proof>
                <p>
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        Suppose there exist two elements <m>e</m> and <m>e'</m> such that <m>ex = x = xe</m> and <m>e'x = x = xe'</m> for all <m>x</m>. Then 
                        <me>
                          e = ee' = e'.
                        </me>
                        Thus only one element can satisfy this property, making the identity element unique.
                      </p>
                    </li>
      
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        For a given <m>x</m>, if <m>yx = xy = e</m> and <m>zx = xz = e</m> fo some <m>y</m> and <m>z</m>, then <m>z = ez = (yx)z = y(xz) = ye = y</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </proof>
            </theorem>
      
            <definition xml:id="def-abelian">
              <title>Abelian Group </title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  A group <m>G</m> is an <em>abelian group</em> if <m>\cdot</m> is commutative; i.e., <m>x \cdot y = y \cdot x</m> for all <m>x,y \in G</m>. Often, but not always, the group operation for an abelian group is written as <m>+</m> instead of <m>\cdot</m>. In this case the inverse of an element <m>x</m> is written <m>-x</m>.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>
      
            <historical>
              <p>
                Abelian groups are named after the Norwegian mathematician Niels Henrik Abel, who made significant contributions to the study of algebra and number theory in the early 19th century.
              </p>
      
              <p>
                Abel's work on abelian groups helped to establish the importance of commutativity in algebraic structures, and his ideas laid the foundation for the development of the theory of commutative rings and fields, which will be studied in much greater depth later.
              </p>
            </historical>

            <example xml:id="ex-group-examples">
              <title>Group Examples</title>
            
                <p>
                  <ol>
                    <li xml:id="trivial-group"> 
                      <p>
                        The <term>trivial subgroup</term> is the group with a single element <m>\{e\}</m>
                        <notation><usage><m>\{e\}</m></usage><description>the trivial group: e.g. the group containing only an identity element</description></notation>          
                      </p>
                    </li>
      
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        <m>(\Z,+), (\Q,+), (\R,+),</m> and <m>(\C,+)</m> are all abelian groups, where <m>+</m> denotes traditional addition.
                      </p>
                    </li>
      
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        <m>\Q^+</m> and <m>\R^+</m> are groups under traditional multiplication.
                      </p>
                    </li>
      
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        For any positive integer <m>n</m>, let 
                        <me>
                          \operatorname{GL}_n(\C)=\{ \text{invertible } n \times n \;\text{matrices with entries in}\; \C\}.
                        </me> 
                        By invertible I mean those matrices that have two-sided inverses, but in turns out that if an <m>n \times n</m> matrix has a left inverse then it it is automatically a right inverse too, and vice versa. Then <m>\operatorname{GL}_n(\C)</m> is a non-abelian group under matrix multiplication.
                        <notation><usage><m>\GL</m></usage><description>General linear group</description></notation> 
                      </p>
                    </li>
      
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        For any <m>n</m>, let <m>\mathbb{Z}/(n)</m> denote the integers modulo <m>n</m>. Then <m>(\mathbb{Z}/(n), +)</m> is an abelian group where <m>+</m> denotes addition modulo <m>n</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
            </example>
            
            <lemma xml:id="lem-group-exponents">
              <title>Group Exponents</title>
              
              <statement>
                <p>
                  If <m>G</m> is a group and <m>x,y,z, a_1,\ldots,a_n \in G</m>, then:
                  <ol>
            
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        <m>(x^{-1})^{-1} = x</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
      
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        <m>x^m\cdot x^n = x^{n+m}</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
      
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        <m>(x^{m})^{n} = x^{mn}</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
            
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        <m>(a_1 \dots a_n)^{-1} = a_n^{-1} \dots a_1^{-1}</m>. Furthermore, if <m>G</m> is abelian then <m>(a_1 \dots a_n)^{-1} = a_1^{-1} \dots a_n^{-1}</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
            
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        <m>(x^{-1}yx)^n = x^{-1}y^nx</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </statement>
