                  These examples are infinite if <m>F</m> is infinite, but if we take <m>F = \mathbb{Z}/p</m> for a prime <m>p</m>, then <m>\operatorname{GL}_n(\mathbb{Z}/p)</m> is a finite group. Can you find its cardinality?
                </p>
              </statement>
            </problem>
            -->
      
            <lemma xml:id="lem-direct-product-group">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>(G,+)</m> and <m>(H,\times)</m> be groups. Then <m>G\times H</m> is a group, where <m>(G\times H,*)</m> denotes the Cartesian Product of <m>G</m> and <m>H</m>, and the operation <m>*</m> is defined 
                  <me>
                    (g_1,h_1)*(g_2,h_2)=(g_1+g_2,h_1\times h_2).
                  </me>
                </p>
              </statement>
      
              <proof>
                <p>
                  Coming soon to an OER near you!
                </p>
              </proof>
            </lemma>
      
            <theorem xml:id="thm-dirprop-gp">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>G_1,\dots,G_n</m> be groups. Then <m>G_1\times\cdots\times G_n</m> is a group, with its operation defined similary to that in <xref ref="lem-direct-product-group"/>
                </p>
              </statement>
      
              <proof>
                <p>
                  Coming soon to an OER near you!
                </p>
              </proof>
            </theorem>
      
            <proposition xml:id="prop-abelian-product-abelian">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  The direct product of groups is abelian if and only if every factor of the product is abelian.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </proposition>
      
            <definition xml:id="def-order">
              <title>Order</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        In a group <m>G</m>, the <em>order of an element</em> <m>x</m> is the least positive integer <m>n</m> such that <m>x^n = e</m>. If no such <m>n</m> exists, we say <m>x</m> has infinite order. We write <m>|x|</m> for the order of <m>x</m>.
                        <notation><usage><m>|x|</m></usage><description>Order of an element <m>x</m></description></notation> 
                      </p>
                    </li>
      
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        The <em>order of a group</em> <m>G</m> is the cardinality of the set <m>G</m>, denoted <m>|G|</m>.
                        <notation><usage><m>|G|</m></usage><description>Order of a group <m>G</m></description></notation> 
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>
      
            <example xml:id="ex-order">
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>|e|=1</m>
                    </p>
                  </li>
      
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>|e|=1</m>
                    </p>
                  </li>
      
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      In the additive groups <m>\Z</m>, <m>\Q</m>, <m>\R</m>, and <m>\C</m> every nonzero (i.e., nonidentity) element has infinite order.
                    </p>
                  </li>
      
                  
                </ol>
      
              </p>
      
            </example>
      
            <theorem xml:id="thm-order-properties">
              <title>Properties of Order</title>
              
              
              <statement>
                <p>
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        An element <m>g</m> of a group <m>G</m> has order <m>1</m> if and only if <m>g=e</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
      
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        <m>|g|=|g\inv|</m>
                      </p>
                    </li>
      
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        If <m>g^=p=e</m> for <m>g\neq e</m> and <m>p</m> prime, then <m>|g|=p</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </theorem>
          
      
            <proposition xml:id="prop-order-4-abelian">
              <title>Marley's Conjecture</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Every group of order <m>4</m> is abelian.
                </p>
              </statement>
        
              <proof>
                <p>
                  Let <m>G</m> be a group with <m>4</m> elements, and suppose there are elements <m>a,b\in G</m> such that <m>ab\neq ba</m> for some elements <m>a, b\in G</m>. Since <m>ab \neq ba</m>, we must have <m>a \neq b</m>, <m>a \neq e</m>, and <m>b\neq e</m>. Since <m>G</m> has only <m>4</m> elements and <m>ab \neq ba</m>, either <m>ab \in \{e, a, b\}</m> or <m>ba \in\{e, a, b\}</m>. Without loss, say the former occurs. But <m>ab = e</m> implies <m>b=a\inv</m> and we know <m>a\inv</m> commutes with <m>a</m>, and hence this is not possible. If <m>ab = a</m>, then <m>b = e</m> and if <m>ab = b</m> then <m>a = 1</m>, both of which are impossible. Since <m>a, b</m> were arbitrary, <m>G</m> must be abelian.
                </p>
              </proof>
            </proposition>
      
            <lemma xml:id="lem-order-lemma">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Let <m>G</m> be a group. Suppose <m>g^k=g^m</m> and <m>k&lt;m</m>.
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        then <m>g^{m-k}=e</m>
                      </p>
                    </li>
      
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        then <m>|g|\leq m-k</m>
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </lemma>
        
