        <section xml:id="sec-gen-cyclic-gp">
          <title>Generators and Cyclic Groups</title>
      
          <introduction>
            <blockquote>
              <p>
                <q>How often misused words generate misleading thoughts.</q>
              </p>
              <attribution>Herbert Spencer</attribution>
            </blockquote>
          </introduction>
      
          <subsection xml:id="subsec-gp-generators">
            <title>Generators</title>
            
          <definition xml:id="def-groupgenerate">
            <title>Generating Set</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                A subset <m>S</m> of a group <m>G</m> is said to <em>generate</em> <m>G</m> if every element of <m>G</m> is equal to a product of elements of <m>S</m> and their inverses (with repetitions allowed). 
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>
      
          <proposition xml:id="prop-d2n-generation">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Prove that <m>D_{2n}</m> is generated by <m>r</m> and any reflection. 
                    </p>
                  </li>
        
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Prove that if <m>p\ge 3</m> is prime then <m>D_{2p}</m> is generated by any two distinct reflections.               
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>
         
          <theorem xml:id="thm-generating-sn">
            <statement>
              <p>
                For <m>n\ge 2</m> prove that <m>S_n</m> is generated by <m>(12)</m> and the <m>n</m>-cycle <m>(12\cdots n)</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>
      
          <remark>
            <p>
              Funnily enough, this theorem will prove extremely useful all the way down in <xref provisional="ch-galois-theory"/>. 
            </p>
