        <section xml:id="sec-quotient-groups">
          <title>Quotient Groups</title>
    
          <p>
            Recall from your undergraduate algebra course the construction for the integers modulo <m>n</m>: one starts with an equivalence relation <m>\sim</m> on <m>\mathbb{Z}</m>, considers the set <m>\mathbb{Z}/n</m> of all equivalence classes with respect to this equivalence relation, and verifies that the operations on <m>\mathbb{Z}</m> give rise to well defined binary operations on the set of equivalence classes.
          </p>
    
          <definition xml:id="def-quotient-group">
            <title>Quotient Group</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                For any normal subgroup <m>N</m> of a group <m>G</m>, the <em>quotient group</em> <m>G/N</m> is <m>G/\sim_N</m>, where <m>\sim_N</m> is the equivalence relation induced by the left action of <m>N</m> on <m>G</m>. In other words, <m>G/N</m> is the set of right cosets of <m>N</m> in <m>G</m> with multiplication given by <m>Nx\cdot Ny=N(xy)</m>. By part 4. of Proposition <xref ref="prop-equivdef-normal" />, <m>G/N</m> is also the set of left cosets of <m>N</m> in <m>G</m> with multiplication given by <m>xN\cdot yN=(xy)N</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>
    
          <theorem xml:id="thm-quotient-iff-normal">
            <title>Quotients and Normal Subgroups</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>N\leq G</m>. Then <m>G/N</m> is a group if and only if <m>N\nsg G</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>
    
          <remark>
            <p>
              Note that the set <m>G/H</m> exists for any subgroup <m>H\leq G</m>. However, this set only satisfies the axioms of a group when the subgroup is normal.
            </p>
          </remark>
    
          <p>
            Recalling <xref ref="thm-lagrange"/>, we have the following corollary:
          </p>
    
          <corollary xml:id="cor-order-of-quotient">
            <title>Order of Quotient Groups</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                By Lagrange's Theorem, if <m>G</m> is finite we have <m>\left | G/N\right |=\frac{|G|}{|N|}</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>
    
          <example>
            <title>The Infinite Dihedral Group</title>
            <p>
              The <em>infinite dihedral group</em> <m>D_\infty</m> is the set <m>D_\infty = \{r^i,r^is \mid i \in \mathbb{Z}\}</m> with multiplication defined by <m>(r^i)(r^j) = r^{i+j}, (r^i)(r^js) = r^{i+j}s, (r^is)(r^j) = r^{i-j}s</m>, and <m>(r^is)(r^js) = r^{i-j}</m>. In other words, <m>D_\infty</m> is the group having presentation <me>D_\infty=\langle r,s \mid s^2=e, srs=r^{-1}\rangle.</me> Then <m>\langle r^n \rangle \mathrel{\unlhd}D_\infty</m> and <m>D_\infty/ \langle r^n \rangle \cong D_{2n}</m> via <m>r\langle r^n \rangle\mapsto r</m> and <m>s\langle r^n \rangle\mapsto s</m>.
            </p>
          </example>
    
          <remark>
            <p>
              In the example above both <m>D_\infty</m> and <m>\langle r^n \rangle</m> are infinite but <m>[D_\infty:\langle r^n \rangle]=\left|D_\infty/\langle r^n \rangle\right|=|D_{2n}|=2n</m>.
            </p>
          </remark>
    
          <definition xml:id="def-quotient-map">
            <title>Quotient Map</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                For any group <m>G</m> and normal subgroup <m>N</m> of <m>G</m> the <em>quotient map</em> <m>\pi:G \to G/N</m> is defined by <m>\pi(g)=gN</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>
    
          <lemma xml:id="lem-quotient-surj-hom">
            <title>Quotient Map is Surjective Homomorphism</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                For any group <m>G</m> and normal subgroup <m>N</m> of <m>G</m>, the map <m>\pi:G \to G/N</m> defined by <m>\pi(g)=gN</m> is a surjective group homomorphism with kernel <m>\operatorname{Ker}(\pi)=N</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
    
            <proof>
              <p>
                Surjectivity is immediate from the definition. The group homomorphism property follows from the computation below which uses the definition of <m>\pi</m> and the rule for multiplying cosets in <m>G/N</m>: <me>\pi(gg')=(gg')N=gN\cdot g'N=\pi(g)\pi(g').</me> Finally, using Lemma <xref ref="lem-cosetfacts" />, we have <m>\operatorname{Ker}(\pi)=\{g\in G\mid gN=e_GN\}=N</m>.
              </p>
            </proof>
          </lemma>
    
          <theorem xml:id="thm-norm-iff-ker">
            <title>Normal Subgroups and Homomorphism Kernels</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                A subgroup <m>N</m> of a group <m>G</m> is normal in <m>G</m> if and only if <m>N</m> is the kernel of a homomorphism with domain <m>G</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
    
            <proof>
              <p>
                Coming soon to an OER near you!
              </p>
            </proof>
          </theorem>
    
          <remark>
            <p>
              Remark on how important this theorem is.
            </p>
          </remark>
    
    
