        <section xml:id="sec-isomorphism-thms">
          <title>The Isomorphism Theorems</title>
    
          <p>
            We come to the so-called Isomorphism Theorems.
          </p>
    
          <theorem xml:id="thm-UMPquot">
            <title>(Universal Mapping Property (UMP) of a Quotient Group)</title>
            
            
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>G</m> be a group and <m>N</m> a normal subgroup. If <m>f: G \to H</m> is a homomorphism of groups such that <m>N \subseteq \operatorname{Ker}(f)</m>, then
              </p>
    
              <p><ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                there exists a unique group homomorphism <m>\overline{f}: G/N \to H</m> such that the composition of <m>\overline{f}</m> and the quotient map <m>{\pi}: G  \twoheadrightarrow G/N</m> is <m>f</m>.
              </p>
                </li>
    
                <li>
                        <p>
                If <m>f</m> is onto, then <m>\overline{f}</m> is onto.
              </p>
                </li>
    
                <li>
                        <p>
                Moreover, <m>\operatorname{Ker}(\overline{f}) = \operatorname{Ker}(f)/N = \{ g N \mid f(g) = e_H\}.</m>
              </p>
                </li>
    
              </ol></p>
    
            </statement>
    
            <proof>
              <p>
                1. If such a <m>\overline{f}</m> exists, it is necessarily unique since <m>G \twoheadrightarrow G/N</m> is onto. In fact, if <m>f=\pi\circ \overline{f}</m> then <m>\overline{f}</m> has to be given by the formula <me>\overline{f}(gN) = f(g).</me> We now need to show that this formula determines a well-defined homomorphism: If <m>xN = yN</m>, then <m>y^{-1}x \in N \subseteq \operatorname{Ker}(f)</m> and so <m>f(y)^{-1} f(x) = e</m>, whence <m>f(y) = f(x)</m>. For any <m>x,y</m> we have <me>\overline{f}(xNyN) = \overline{f}(xyN) = f(xy) = f(x)f(y) =\overline{f}(xN) \overline{f}(yN).</me>
              </p>
    
              <p>
                2. The formula for <m>\overline{f}</m> given above ensures that <m>\operatorname{Im}f=\operatorname{Im}\overline{f}</m> hence <m>f</m> is surjective if and only if <m>\overline{f}</m> is surjective.
              </p>
    
              <p>
                3. We have <m>\overline{f}(xN) = e_H</m> iff <m>f(x) = e_H</m> iff <m>x \in \operatorname{Ker}(f)</m> iff <m>xN \in  \operatorname{Ker}(f)/N</m>. If <m>xN \in \operatorname{Ker}(f)/N</m> for some <m>x \in G</m>, then <m>xN = yN</m> for some <m>y \in \operatorname{Ker}(f)</m> and hence <m>x = yz</m> for some <m>z \in N</m>. Since <m>N \subseteq \operatorname{Ker}(f)</m>, we have <m>x \in \operatorname{Ker}(f)</m>. ◻
              </p>
    
            </proof>
          </theorem>
    
          <example>
            <p>
              Let <m>G</m> be any group. For <m>x,y \in G</m>, set <m>[x,y] = xyx^{-1}y^{-1}</m>. Let <m>G'</m> denote the <em>commutator subgroup</em> of <m>G</m> generated by all elements of the form <m>[x,y]</m> for <m>x,y \in G</m>. (Some people write <m>G'</m> as <m>[G,G]</m>.) Then <m>G'</m> is in fact normal: <m>G' \unlhd G</m>. Now let <m>f: G \to A</m> be any group homomorphism from <m>G</m> to an abelian group <m>A</m>. Since <m>f([x,y]) = [f(x),f(y)] = e</m> for all <m>x, y \in G</m> (since <m>A</m> is abelian), we have that <m>\operatorname{Ker}(f)</m> must contain <m>G'</m>. By the UMP for quotients, we get that <m>f</m> factors as <me>f:G \xrightarrow{{\pi}} G/G' \xrightarrow{\overline{f}} A</me> for a unique group homomorphism <m>\overline{f}</m>.
            </p>
    
            <p>
              The group <m>G/G'</m> is called the <em>abelianization of <m>G</m></em> and the motto is: A homomorphism from a group to an abelian group factors uniquely through the abelianization.
            </p>
    
          </example>
    
          <theorem xml:id="thm-fit-group">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>f: G \to H</m> is a homomorphism of groups, then <m>\operatorname{Ker}(g)\mathrel{\unlhd}G</m> and the map <m>\overline{f}</m> defined by the UMP induces an isomorphism <me>\overline{f}: G/\operatorname{Ker}(f) \xrightarrow{\cong} \operatorname{Im}(f).</me>
              </p>
            </statement>
    
            <proof>
              <p>
                By the UMP, there exists a homomorphism <m>\overline{f}</m> such that <m>\overline{f} \circ {\pi}= f</m>, and its kernel consists of just the one element <m>\operatorname{Ker}(f)/\operatorname{Ker}(f)</m> of <m>G/\operatorname{Ker}(f)</m>. So <m>\overline{f}</m> is one-to-one, and the image of <m>\overline{f}</m> is clearly the same as the image of <m>f</m>. ◻
              </p>
            </proof>
          </theorem>
    
          <p>
            The first isomorphism theorem, also known as the homomorphism theorem, is named as such because it was the first major result in the theory of group homomorphisms and was discovered before the second and third isomorphism theorems. 
          </p>
    
          <proposition xml:id="prop-normal-hk">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>H\leq G</m> and <m>K\leq G</m> then <m>HK\leq G</m> if and only if <m>HK=KH</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
        
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>H\leq G</m> and <m>K\leq G</m> and either one of <m>H</m> or <m>K</m> is a normal subgroup then <m>HK\leq G</m> and <m>HK=KH=\langle H\cup K\rangle</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>
    
          <warning>
            <p>
              The identity <m>HK=KH</m> does not mean that every pair of elements from <m>H</m> and <m>K</m> must commute.
            </p>
          </warning>
    
          <example>
            <p>
              In <m>D_{2n}</m>, let <m>H=\langle s\rangle</m> and <m>K=\langle r\rangle</m>. Then <m>HK=KH=D_{2n}</m> but of course <m>r</m> and <m>s</m> do not commute. The fact that <m>HK=KH</m> can also be justified by observing that <m>K\mathrel{\unlhd}D_{2n}</m>.
            </p>
          </example>
    
          <p>
            The second isomorphism theorem, also known as the diamond isomorphism theorem or the modular law, provides information about the structure of subgroups and their intersections.
          </p>
    
          <theorem xml:id="thm-sit-group">
            <title>Second Isomorphism Theorem</title>
            
            
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>G</m> be a group, <m>H \leq G</m> and <m>N \unlhd G</m>. Then <m>HN \leq G</m>, <m>N \cap H \unlhd H</m>, <m>N \unlhd HN</m> and there is an isomorphism 
                <me>
                  \frac{H}{N \cap H} \xrightarrow{\cong} \frac{HN}{N}</me> given by <me>h \cdot (N \cap H) \mapsto hN.
                </me>
              </p>
            </statement>
    
            <proof>
              <p>
              The first two assertions are left as exercises and since <m>N \unlhd G</m> we have <m>N \unlhd HN</m>. Define a homomorphism <m>f: H \to \frac{HN}{N}</m> by <m>f(h) = hN</m>. This is a homomorphism since it is the composition 
              <me>
                f:H \hookrightarrow HN \xrightarrow{{\pi}} \frac{HN}{N}
              </me> 
              of homomorphisms. <m>f</m> is onto since for all <m>h,n</m> we have <m>hnN = hN = f(h)</m>. The kernel of <m>f</m> is <m>\operatorname{Ker}(f)=\{h \mid hN = N\} = H \cap N</m>. The result thus follows from the first isomorphism theorem.
            </p>
            </proof>
          </theorem>
    
          <corollary xml:id="cor-order-of-hn">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If <m>H</m>and <m>N</m> are finite subgrups of <m>G</m> and <m>N\mathrel{\unlhd}G</m>, then <m>|HN |= \frac{|H|\cdot |N| }{\left|H \cap N\right|}</m>. (In fact this is also true without the requirement that <m>N</m> be normal.)
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>
    
          <p>
            The third isomorphism theorem, also known as the factor or quotient theorem, gives a relationship between normal subgroups of a group and their quotient groups.
          </p>
          
          <theorem xml:id="thm-tit-group">
            <title>Third Isomorphism Theorem</title>
            
            
            <statement>
              <p>
                Suppose <m>G</m> is a group, <m>M \leq N \leq G</m>, <m>M \unlhd G</m> and <m>N \unlhd G</m>. Then <m>M \unlhd N</m>, <m>N/M \unlhd G/M</m> and there is an isomorphism 
                <me>
                  (G/M)/(N/M) \xrightarrow{\cong} G/N
                </me>
                given by sending the coset of <m>(G/M)/(N/M)</m> represented by <m>gM</m> to <m>gN</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
    
            <proof>
              <p>
                The first two assertions are immediate from the definitions.
              </p>
    
              <p>
                The kernel of the canonical map <m>{\pi}: G \twoheadrightarrow G/N</m> contains <m>M</m> and so by the UMP for quotients we get an induced homomorhism 
                <me>
                  \phi: G/M \to G/N
                </me>
                with <m>\phi(gM) = {\pi}(g) = gN</m>. Moreover, we know 
                <me>
                  \operatorname{Ker}(\phi) = \operatorname{Ker}({\pi})/M = N/M.
                </me> 
                Finally apply the First Isomorphism Theorem to <m>\phi</m>.
              </p>
            </proof>
          </theorem>
    
          <remark>
            <p>
              In the realm of group theory, the First Isomorphism Theorem is by far the most widely used. While important, the Second and Third Isomorphism Theorems do not pop up all that often in this text. 
            </p>
          </remark>
    
          <theorem xml:id="thm-lattice-iso-group">
            <title>The Lattice Isomorphism Theorem</title>
            
            
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>G</m> be a group and <m>N</m> a normal subgroup with canonical homomorphism <m>\pi:G\to G/N</m>. There is an containment-preserving bijection 
                <me>
                  \Psi:\{\text{subgroups of}\; G \;\text{that contain}\; N}\} \xrightarrow{\text{bijective}}\{\text{subgroups of}\; G/N\}
                </me> 
                given by <m>\Psi(H)= H/N</m> for <m>N \leq H \leq G</m>. The inverse is defined for <m>\mathcal{H}\leq G/N</m> by 
                <me>
                  \Phi(\mathcal{H})=\pi^{-1}(\mathcal{H}) = \{x \in G \mid \pi(x) \in \mathcal{H}\}
                </me> 
                where <m>\pi: G \twoheadrightarrow G/N</m> is the quotient map. We denote <m>\Psi(H)=H/N=\overline{H}</m>.
              </p>
    
              <p>
                Then this bijection enjoys the following properties:
              </p>
        
              <p><ol>
                <li>
                        <p>
                (normal) subgroups correspond to normal subgroups i.e.,
              </p>
        
              <p><ul>
                <li>
                        <p>
                <m>H\leq G</m> iff <m>\overline{H}\leq \overline{G}</m> and <m>\mathcal{H}\leq \overline{G}</m> iff <m>\Phi(\mathcal{H})\leq G</m>
              </p>
                </li>
        
                <li>
                        <p>
                <m>H\mathrel{\unlhd}G</m> iff <m>\overline{H}\mathrel{\unlhd}\overline{G}</m> and <m>\mathcal{H}\mathrel{\unlhd}\overline{G}</m> iff <m>\Phi(\mathcal{H})\mathrel{\unlhd}G</m>
              </p>
                </li>
        
              </ul></p>
                </li>
        
                <li>
                        <p>
                indices are preserved; i.e., <m>[G:H] = [\overline{G} : \overline{H}]</m> and <m>[G: \Phi(\mathcal{H})] = [\overline{G} : \mathcal{H}]</m>.
              </p>
                </li>
        
                <li>
                        <p>
                the supremums and infimums are preserved (this makes <m>\Phi</m> and <m>\Psi</m> lattice isomorphisms)
              </p>
        
              <p><ul>
                <li>
                        <p>
                <m>\overline{H} \cap \overline{K} = \overline{H \cap H}</m> and <m>\langle \overline{H}\cup \overline{K} \rangle = \overline{\langle H\cup K \rangle}</m>
              </p>
                </li>
        
                <li>
                        <p>
                <m>\Phi(\mathcal{H}) \cap \Phi(\mathcal K) = \Phi(\mathcal{H}\cap \mathcal K)</m> and <m>\langle \Phi(\mathcal{H})\cup\Phi(\mathcal K) \rangle = \Phi\left(\langle \mathcal{H}\cup\mathcal K\rangle\right)</m>
              </p>
                </li>
        
              </ul></p>
                </li>
        
              </ol></p>
            </statement>
    
            <proof>
              <p>
                We have previously shown that the quotient map <m>\pi:G\to G/N</m> is a surjective group homomorphism. We show:
              </p>
        
              <p><ul>
                <li>
                <p>
                <m>\Psi</m> is well defined (correct codomain) since for <m>H\leq G</m> we have <m>\pi(H)\leq G/N</m> (since images of subgroups through group homomorphisms are subgroups).
              </p>
                </li>
        
                <li>
                        <p>
                <m>\Phi</m> is well defined (correct codomain) since for <m>\mathcal{H}\leq G</m> we have <m>\pi^{-1}(\mathcal{H})\leq G</m> (since preimages of subgroups through group homomorphisms are subgroups) and for any <m>\mathcal{H}\leq G</m> we have <m>\{e_GN\}\subseteq \mathcal{H}</m>, hence 
                <me>
                  N=\operatorname{Ker}(\pi)=\pi^{-1}(\{e_GN\})\subseteq \pi^{-1}(\mathcal{H})=\Phi(\mathcal{H}).
                </me>
              </p>
                </li>
        
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>\Phi</m> and <m>\Psi</m> are mutual inverses: <m>(\Psi\circ\Phi)(\mathcal{H})=\pi(\pi^{-1}(\mathcal{H}))=\mathcal{H}</m> since <m>\pi</m> is surjective and <m>(\Phi\circ\Psi)(H)=\pi^{-1}(\pi(H))=\pi^{-1}(H/N)=H</m>, with the last equality justified by 
                    <me>
                      \begin{aligned}
                      x\in \pi^{-1}(H/N) &amp;\iff \pi(x)\in H/N \iff xN=hN \text{ for some } h\in H \\
                      &amp; \iff x\in hN \text{ for some } h\in H \iff x\in H \text{ (using that } N\subseteq H).\\
                      \end{aligned}
                    </me>
              </p>
                </li>
        
              </ul></p>
        
              <p>
                Thus, the two functions defined in the statement are well-defined and are mutually inverse.
              </p>
    
              <p>
                Since <m>\pi</m> and <m>\pi^{-1}</m> preserve containments, each of <m>\Psi</m>, <m>\Psi^{-1}</m> preserves the order relation of containment.
              </p>
        
              <p>
                I will only prove some parts of statements (1), (2), (3) in the theorem.
              </p>
        
              <p>
                (1) If <m>N \leq H \leq G</m> and <m>H \unlhd G</m>, then <m>H/N \unlhd G/N</m> holds by part of the 3rd Isomorphism Theorem or by the exercise below, since <m>\pi</m> is surjective. The fact that the inverse function also sends normal subgroups to normal subgroups is a consequence of the statement that inverse images of normal subgroups are normal subgroups (see HW 4).
              </p>
        
              <p>
                (2) In the interest of time, I'll only prove the assertion about indices in the special case when <m>H</m> is normal. In that case this fact is also an immediate consequence of the Third Isomorhism Theorem since for <m>N \leq H \leq G</m> with <m>H \unlhd G</m> we have <me>[G:H] = |G/H| = \left|(G/N)/(H/N)\right| = [G/N: H/N]=[\overline{G}:\overline{H}].</me> The general case is a consequence of an exercise from HW 5.
              </p>
        
              <p>
                (3) The proof of (3) is omitted.
              </p>
            </proof>
          </theorem>
    
