      <chapter xml:id="group-actions">
      <title>Group Actions</title>
  
      <section xml:id="graction">
        <title>Group Actions</title>
  
        <blockquote>
          <p>
            <q>Actions speak louder than words.</q>
          </p>
          <attribution>Anthony of Padua</attribution>
        </blockquote>
  
        <definition xml:id="def-graction">
          <title>Group Action</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              For a group <m>(G, \cdot)</m> and set <m>S</m>, an <em>action</em> of <m>G</m> on <m>S</m> is a function <me>G \times S \to S,</me> typically written as <m>(g,s) \mapsto g \cdot s</m>, such that
            </p>
        
            <p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>g \cdot (g' \cdot s) = (g g') \cdot s</m> for all <m>g,g' \in G</m> and <m>s\in S</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
      
                <li>
                  <p>
                    <m>e_G \cdot s = s</m> for all <m>s \in S</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>
  
        <remark>
          <p>
            To make the first axiom clearer, throughout this section we will write <m>\cdot</m> for the action of <m>G</m> on <m>S</m> and no symbol (concatenation) for the multiplication of two elements in the group <m>G</m>.
          </p>
        </remark>
  
        <example>
          <title>Trivial Action</title>
          
          <p>
            For any group <m>G</m> and any set <m>S</m>, <m>g \cdot s := s</m> defines an action, the <em>trivial action</em>. The associated group homomorphism is <m>G \to \operatorname{Perm}(S)</m> by <m>g\mapsto \text{id}_S</m>.
          </p>
        </example>
  
        <theorem xml:id="thm-permrep">
          <title>The Permutation Representation</title>
          
          <statement>
            <p>
              Assume <m>(G, \cdot)</m> is a group and <m>S</m> is a set.
            </p>
            <p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If <m>\cdot</m> is an action of <m>G</m> on <m>S</m>, then the function <m>\rho: G \to \operatorname{Perm}(S)</m> defined as <m>\rho(g) = \sigma_g</m>, where <m>\sigma_g:S\to S</m> is the function given by <m>\sigma_g(s)=g \cdot s</m>, is a well defined homomorphism of groups.
                  </p>
                </li>
      
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Conversely, if <m>\rho: G \to \operatorname{Perm}(S)</m> is a group homomorphism, the rule <m>g \cdot s := \rho(g)(s)</m> defines an action of <m>G</m> on <m>S</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </statement>
  
          <proof>
            <p>
              We have 
              <me>
                \begin{aligned}
                (\sigma_g\circ\sigma_{g^{-1}})(s) &amp;=\sigma_g(\sigma_{g^{-1}}(s)) &amp; \text{ (def of composition)}\\
                &amp;=g\cdot (g^{-1} \cdot s) &amp; \text{ (def for } \sigma_g \text{ and } \sigma_{g^{-1}})\\
                &amp;=(gg^{-1})\cdot s &amp; \text{ (first property of a group action)}\\
                &amp;=e_G\cdot s &amp; \text{ (group axiom)}\\
                &amp;= s &amp;\text{ (second property of a group action)}
                \end{aligned}
              </me> 
              thus <m>\sigma_g\circ\sigma_{g^{-1}}=\text{id}_S</m> and a similar argument shows that <m>\sigma_{g^{-1}}\circ\sigma_{g}=\text{id}_S</m>
            </p>
                
            <p>
              Finally, we wish to show <m>\rho(gg')=\rho(g) \circ \rho(g')</m>, equivalently <m>\sigma_{gg'}=\sigma_g\circ\sigma_{g'}</m>. Since <me>\sigma_{gg'}(s) = (gg')\cdot s = g\cdot(g'\cdots) =\sigma_g\left(\sigma_{g'}(s)\right) = (\sigma_g\circ\sigma_{g'})(s),</me> holds for all <m>s</m>, this proves <m>\rho</m> is a homomorphism.
            </p>
                
            <p>
              Given a homomorphism <m>\rho</m>, the function <m>G \times S \to S</m> defined as <m>g \cdot s = \rho(g)(s)</m> is an action because <m>g'(gs) = \rho(g')(\rho(g)(s)) = (\rho(g') \circ\rho(g))(s) = \rho(gg')(s) = (gg')s</m>, and <m>e_G s = \rho(e_G)(s) = \text{id}(s) = s</m>.
            </p>
          </proof>
  
        </theorem>
  
        <p>
          Permutation representations are one the most essential benefits of group actions. This homomorphism allows us to study the structure of a group <m>G</m> by looking at the permutation group of <m>X</m>, which may be a more manageable group to work with. 
          <notation><usage><m>\rho</m></usage><description>The permutation representation of a group action</description></notation> 
        </p>
  
        <definition xml:id="def-faithful-action">
          <title>Faithful Action</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              An action of a group <m>G</m> on a set <m>S</m> is called <em>faithful</em> if the associated group homomorphism is injective. Equivalently, an action is faithful if and only if for a given <m>g \in G</m>, whenever <m>g \cdot s = s</m> for all <m>s \in S</m>, it must be that <m>g = e_G</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>
  
        <definition xml:id="def-transitive-action">
          <title>Transitive Action</title>
          <statement>
            <p>
              An action is <em>transitive</em> if for all <m>p,q \in S</m> there is a <m>g \in G</m> such that <m>q=g\cdot p</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </definition>
  
        <p>
          Transitive and faithful actions are important concepts in group theory because they allow us to understand the structure of a group by examining its action on a set, and they correspond to important situations where a group is acting in a way that respects the symmetry and structure of a mathematical object.
        </p>
  
        <remark>
          <p>
            In many cases, transitivity and faithfulness are related concepts. As we will see later, if a group action is transitive on a set <m>X</m>, then the action is faithful if and only if the stabilizer of any element of <m>X</m> is trivial. In these situations we can identify the group with a subgroup of the symmetric group on <m>X</m>, and use this identification to study the group.
          </p>
        </remark>
  
        <example xml:id="ex-transitive-faithful-actions">
          <title>Transitive and Faithful Actions</title>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The action of the group of rotational symmetries of a regular polygon on the vertices of the polygon is transitive. Any vertex can be sent to any other vertex by a rotation of the polygon.
                </p>
              </li>
  
              <li>
                <p>
                  The action of the group of rigid motions of three-dimensional space on the points of a sphere is transitive. Any point on the sphere can be sent to any other point by a rotation or translation of space.              
                </p>
              </li>
  
              <li>
                <p>
                  The action of the group of invertible <m>2\times2</m> matrices on the complex plane by multiplication is faithful. Every non-identity matrix corresponds to a different transformation of the complex plane.              
                </p>
              </li>
  
              <li>
                <p>
                  The action of the group of permutations of a set <m>X</m> on the set <m>X</m> itself by permutation is faithful. Every permutation corresponds to a unique rearrangement of the elements of <m>X</m>.              
                </p>
              </li>
  
              <li>
                <p>
                  The action of the group of permutations of a set <m>X</m> on the set of all subsets of <m>X</m> by permutation is both transitive and faithful. Any subset can be sent to any other subset by permuting the elements of <m>X</m>, and every non-identity permutation corresponds to a different permutation of the subsets of <m>X</m>.             
                 </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
  
        </example>
  
