      <section xml:id="sec-self-actions">
        <title>Self Actions</title>
  
        <introduction>
          <blockquote>
            <p>
              <q>You may never know what results come of your action, but if you do nothing there will be no results.</q>
            </p>
            <attribution>Ghandi</attribution>
          </blockquote>
        </introduction>
  
        <subsection xml:id="subsec-conjugation-action">
          <title>Self Conjugation</title>
  
          <definition xml:id="def-conjugacy-class">
            <title>Conjugacy Class</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                The <em>conjugacy class</em> of an element <m>g \in G</m> is <m>C_G(g) = \{hgh^{-1} \mid h \in G\}</m>.
                <notation><usage><m>C_G(g)</m></usage><description>the conjugacy class of the element <m>g\in G=\{hgh^{-1} \mid h \in G\}</m></description></notation>          
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>
    
          <definition xml:id="def-conjugate">
            <title>Conjugate</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>G</m> be a group. Two elements <m>g,g' \in G</m> are <em>conjugate</em> if there is <m>h \in G</m> with <m>g' = hgh^{-1}</m> (equivalently <m>g</m> and <m>g'</m> are in the same orbit of the conjugation action).
              </p>
    
              <p>
                Two subsets <m>S,S' \subseteq G</m> are conjugate if there is <m>h \in G</m> with <m>S' = hSh^{-1}</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>
          
  
          <example>
            <title>Conjugation Action</title>
            
            <p>
              Let <m>G</m> be any group and fix an element <m>g \in G</m>. Define <em>the conjugation action</em> of <m>G</m> on itself by setting 
              <me>
                g\cdot x=gxg^{-1} \;\text{for any}\; g,x\in G.
              </me> 
            </p>
          </example>
    
          <theorem xml:id="thm-conjugation-action">
            <title>Induced Conjugations</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Prove that the conjugation action of of <m>G</m> on itself is a well-defined group action.
                    </p>
                  </li>
      
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Show <m>G</m> acts on <m>H</m> via conjugation for any <m>H\leq G</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
    
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Let <m>N\mathrel{\unlhd}G</m>. The conjugation action of <m>G</m> on itself induces an action by conjugation of <m>G</m> on <m>N</m>. In particular, <m>N</m> is the disjoint union of some of the conjugacy classes in <m>G</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>
    
          <proposition xml:id="prop-kernel-of-conjugation-action">
            <title>Conjugation Kernel</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                The kernel of the permutation representation for the conjugation action is the center <m>Z(G)</m>. 
              </p>
            </statement>
    
            <proof>
              <p>
                If <m>\rho:G\to \operatorname{Perm}(G)</m> is the permutation representation for <m>G</m> acting on <m>G</m> by conjugation, then 
                <me>
                  g\in \operatorname{Ker}\rho\iff g\cdot x=x, \forall x\in G \iff gxg^{-1}=x, \forall x\in G
                </me>
                <me>
                  \iff gx=xg, \forall x\in G \iff g\in Z(G).
                </me>
              </p>
            </proof>
          </proposition>
    
          <corollary xml:id="cor-faithful-conjugation">
            <title>Faithful Conjugations</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                The action of <m>G</m> on itself by conjugation is faithful if and only if <m>Z(G)=\{e\}</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </corollary>
    
        </subsection>
  
        <subsection xml:id="subsec-left-multiplication">
          <title>Left Regualr Action</title>
  
          <example xml:id="ex-leftreg">
            <title>Left Regular Action</title>
            
            <p>
              Let <m>G</m> be any group and define an action <m>\cdot</m> of <m>G</m> on <m>G</m> (regarded as just a set) by the rule 
              <me>
                g \cdot x = g  x, \;\text{for}\; g \in G \;\text{and}\; x \in G.
              </me>
            </p>
          </example>
  
          <remark>
            <p>
              This action is often referred to as left multiplcation.
            </p>
          </remark>
  
          <proposition xml:id="prop-left-mult-well-defined">
            <title>Left Multiplication is Faithful</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Prove that the left regular action is a well defined action.
                    </p>
                  </li>
  
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Prove that the left regular action is faithful.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>
  
          <lemma xml:id="lem-largest-normal-subgroup">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>H</m> be a subgroup of a group <m>G</m>, and let <m>G</m> act on the set <m>G/H</m> of left cosets by left multiplication <m>g \cdot (g'H) = (gg')H</m>. Let <m>\rho: G\to \Perm(G/H)</m> denote the permutation representation associated to this action. Then
              </p>
  
              <p>
                <ol>
                <li>
                the action described above is transitive
                </li>
  
                <li>
                <m>\ker(\rho) = \bigcap_{g \in G} gHg^{-1}</m>
                </li>
  
                <li>
                the subgroup described in (a) is the largest (with respect to containment) normal subgroup of <m>G</m> contained in <m>H</m>.
                </li>
  
              </ol>
            </p>
  
            </statement>
          </lemma>
  
          <proposition xml:id="prop-normal-subgroups-and-index">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>G</m> be a group, and let <m>H</m> be a subgroup of <m>G</m> of finite index <m>[G:H] = n</m>. Show that there exists a normal subgroup <m>N\norm G</m> such that <m>N \leq H</m> and <m>[G:N] \leq n!</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>
         
          <theorem xml:id="thm-smallest-prime-normal">
            <title>Smallest Prime Index is Normal</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>G</m> be a finite group and let <m>H</m> be a subgroup of <m>G</m> of index <m>p</m>, where <m>p</m> is the smallest prime divisor of the order of <m>G</m>. Prove that <m>H</m> is normal in <m>G</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
      
            <proof>
              <p>
                Let <m>S=G/H</m> and note that <m>|S|=p</m>. Let <m>K</m> denote the kernel of the permutation representation generated by <m>G</m> acting on <m>S</m> by left multiplication.
              </p>
      
              <p>
                The First Isomorphism Theorem tells us that <m>G/K\cong\im(\rho)\leq S_p</m>. Thus <m>|K|\big|p!</m> by Lagrange's Theorem. Let <m>k\in K</m>. Then <m>kgH=gH</m> for all <m>g\in G</m>, making <m>k\in gHg\inv</m> for all <m>g\in G,</m> including <m>e</m>. Thus <m>K\nsg H</m>.
              </p>
      
              <p>
                This yields <m>[G:K]=[G:H][H:K]</m>. Let <m>h=[H:K]</m>, giving us <m>[G:K]=ph</m>. As <m>|K|\big|p!</m> we have <m>h|(p-1)!</m>, so <m>h&lt;p</m>. But <m>p</m> is the smallest prime dividing the order of <m>G</m>, and thus <m>h=1</m>, making <m>H=K</m> and <m>H\nsg G</m>.
              </p>
            </proof>
           </theorem>
  
           <remark>
            <p>
              Proving this theorem was Problem () on the Qual and Problem () on the Qual
            </p>
           </remark>
  
  
        </subsection>
  
