          <blockquote>
            <p>
              <q>What makes me unique is that I'm normal.</q>
            </p>
            <attribution>Scotty McCreery</attribution>
          </blockquote>
    
          <lemma xml:id="lem-Sylaction">
            <title>Unique Order Subgroups are Normal</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Suppose <m>G</m> is a group and <m>n</m> is a positive integer. Then
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>H\leq G</m> is a subgroup of order <m>n</m>, then <m>gHg^{-1}\leq G</m> is a subgroup of order <m>n</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
    
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If there is a unique subgroup <m>H</m> of <m>G</m> of order <m>n</m>, then <m>H \unlhd G</m>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </lemma>
    
          <lemma xml:id="lem-Syl-lem">
            <title>Sylow's Lemma</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>G</m> be a finite group, <m>p</m> a prime, <m>P</m> a Sylow <m>p</m>-subgroup of <m>G</m>, and <m>Q</m> any <m>p</m>-subgroup of <m>G</m>. Then <m>Q \cap N_G(P) = Q \cap P</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </lemma>
    
          <theorem xml:id="thm-sylow">
            <title>Sylow's Theorem</title>
            
            <statement>
              <p>
                Assume <m>G</m> is a group of order <m>p^e m</m> where <m>p</m> is prime, <m>e \geq 0</m>, and <m>\operatorname{gcd}(p,m) = 1</m>.
    
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>\operatorname{Syl}_p(G) \ne \emptyset</m> (there exists at least one Sylow <m>p</m>-subgroup of <m>G</m>).
                    </p>
                  </li>
    
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If <m>P</m> is a Sylow <m>p</m>-subgroup of <m>G</m> and <m>Q \leq G</m> is any <m>p</m>-subgroup of <m>G</m> (i.e., a subgroup whose order is some power of <m>p</m>), then there is a <m>g</m> such that <m>Q \leq gPg^{-1}</m>. In particular, the action of <m>G</m> on <m>\operatorname{Syl}_p(G)</m> by conjugation is transitive — i.e., any two Sylow <m>p</m>-subgroups are conjugate.
                    </p>
                  </li>
    
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      We have <me>| \operatorname{Syl}_p(G)| \equiv 1 \mod{p}.</me>
                    </p>
                  </li>
    
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      For any <m>P \in \operatorname{Syl}_p(G)</m>, 
                      <me>
                        |\operatorname{Syl}_p(G)| = [G: N_G(P)],
                      </me> 
                      and hence 
                      <me>
                        | \operatorname{Syl}_p(G)| \mid m.
                      </me>
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>
    
          <p>
            Sylow's theorems provide a systematic way of analyzing the subgroups of a finite group. They allow us to determine the number of subgroups of a given order, which is useful in many applications, such as studying the structure of solvable and simple groups. The theorems also provide information about the normalizers of subgroups, which can be used to study normal subgroups and quotient groups.
          </p>
    
