        <section xml:id="sec-defn-ex">
            <title>Intro to Rings</title>
    
            <subsection xml:id="subsec-first-ex">
                <title>Definition and First Properties</title>
                
            
    
                <definition xml:id="def-ring">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A <em>ring</em> is a set <m>R</m> equipped with two binary operations, <m>+</m> and <m>\cdot</m>, satisfying:
                    </p>
    
                    <p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>(R,+)</m> is an <em>abelian</em> group with identity element denoted <m>0</m>,
                                </p>
                            </li>
    
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\cdot</m> is associative (making <m>(R,\cdot)</m> a semigroup)
                                </p>
                            </li>
    
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>a \cdot (b + c) = a \cdot b + a \cdot c</m> and <m>(a + b) \cdot c = a \cdot c + b \cdot c</m> hold for all <m>a,b,c \in R</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
    
                    <p>
                        <m>R</m> is a <em>unital ring</em> (or a <em>ring with identity</em>) if, in addition to (1), (2), (3)
                    </p>
    
                    <p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    there is a multiplicative identity element written as <m>1</m> such that <m>1 \cdot a = a = a \cdot 1</m> for all <m>a \in R</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
    
                    <p>
                        <m>R</m> is <em>commutative</em> if in addition to (1)-(3)
                    </p>
    
                    <p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>a \cdot b = b \cdot a</m> holds for all <m>a,b \in R</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                </p>
    
                    <p>
                        <m>R</m> is a <em>division ring</em> if <m>1\neq 0</m>, (1)–(4) and (6) hold
                    </p>
    
                    <p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>(R - \{0\})</m> is a group under <m>\cdot</m> (i.e. every <m>r\in (R - \{0\})</m> has a multiplicative inverse)
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
    
                    <p>
                        <m>R</m> is a <em>field</em> if <m>1\neq 0</m> and (1)–(6) hold (i.e. a field is a commutative division ring).
                    </p>
                </statement>
                </definition>
    
                <problem xml:id="exe-commutativity-of-addition">
                <p>
                Commutativity of addition is a consequence of the other ring axioms in rings with <m>1</m>.
                </p>
                </problem>
    
                <p>
                    Here are some basic consequences of the axioms.
                </p>
    
                <proposition xml:id="prop-ring-arithmetic">
                    <title>Ring Arithmetic</title>
                    
                    
                    <statement>
                    <p>
                        For any ring <m>R</m> and all <m>a,b \in R</m> we have:
                    </p>
    
                    <p>
                      <ol>
                        <li>
                          <p>
                            <m>a \cdot 0 = 0 = 0 \cdot a</m>,
                          </p>
                        </li>
            
                        <li>
                          <p>
                            <m>(-a)b = -(ab) = a(-b)</m>,
                          </p>
                        </li>
            
                        <li>
                          <p>
                            <m>(-a)(-b) = ab</m>.
                          </p>
                        </li>
                      </ol>
                    </p>
            
                    <p>
                      If moreover <m>R</m> is unital, then
                    </p>
              
                    <p>
                      <ol>
                        <li>
                          <p>
                            <m>1</m> is unique, and
                          </p>
                        </li>
            
                        <li>
                          <p>
                            <m>(-1)a = -a</m>.
                          </p>
                        </li>
                      </ol>
                    </p>
                    </statement>
    
                    <proof>
                      <p>
                        Let <m>R</m> be a ring with identity.
    
                        <ol>
                          <li>
                            <p>
                              Let <m>a\in R</m>. Observe that <m>0a=(0+0)a=0a+0a</m> by the distributive law. Subtracting <m>0a</m> from both sides we have <m>0=0a</m>. A similar argument shows that <m>0=a0</m>.
                            </p>
                          </li>
    
                          <li>
                            <p>
                              Let <m>a\in R</m>. Note that <m>-a+a=0</m>. Consider <m>(-1)a+a</m>. Using the distributive law we see that <m>(-1)a+a=a(-1+1)=a(0)=0</m>. Thus <m>-a</m> and <m>(-1)a</m> are both additive inverses of <m>a,</m> making them unique.
                            </p>
                          </li>
    
                          <li>
                            <p>
                              
                            </p>
                          </li>
                        </ol>
                      </p>
                    </proof>
                </proposition>
    
                <example xml:id="ex-ring-examples">
                    <p><ol>
                    <li>
                            <p>
                    <m>R=\{0\}</m> is called the <em>trivial ring</em>. Notice that in the trivial ring <m>0=1</m>. Conversely, if <m>1 = 0</m> in a ring, then <m>R = \{0\}</m>, since in this case for all <m>a</m>, we have <m>a \cdot 0 = 0</m> and hence <m>a = a \cdot 1 = a \cdot 0 = 0</m>.
                    </p>
                    </li>
    
                    <li>
                            <p>
                    <m>\mathbb{Z}</m> is a commutative ring.
                    </p>
                    </li>
    
                    <li>
                            <p>
                    <m>\mathbb{Z}/n</m> is a commutative ring under addition and multiplication modulo <m>n</m>. Note that <m>\mathbb{Z}/n</m> is a field if any only if <m>n</m> is prime.
                    </p>
                    </li>
    
                    <li>
                            <p>
                    The familiar sets of “numbers" <m>\mathbb{Q}, {\mathbb{R}}, \mathbb{C}</m> are fields.
                    </p>
                    </li>
    
                    <li>
                            <p>
                    (<term>Matrix ring</term>) If <m>R</m> is any ring (not necessarily commutative), so is <m>\operatorname{M}_{n}(R)</m> for any natural number <m>n</m>, using the usual rules for addition and multiplication of square matrices.
                    </p>
                    </li>
    
                    <li>
                            <p>
                    (<term>The real Hamiltonian quaternion ring</term>) Let <m>i,j,k</m> be formal symbols and set <m>{\mathbb{H}}</m> to be the four dimensional <m>{\mathbb{R}}</m>-vector space consisting of all expressions of the form <m>a + bi + cj + dk</m> with <m>a,b,c,d \in {\mathbb{R}}</m>. Addition is vector space addition: <me>(a + bi + cj + dk) +(a' + b'i + c'j + d'k) =
            (a + a') + (b + b') i + (c + c')j + (d + d')k.</me> Multiplication is uniquely determined by the axioms of a ring together with the rules <me>i^2 = j^2 = k^2 = -1, -ji = ij = k, -kj = jk = i, -ik = ki = j.</me> and the fact that the real coefficients commute with each other and <m>i,j,k</m>.
                    </p>
    
                    <p>
                    It's not obvious that the multiplication defined in this way satisfies associativity, but in fact it does (this amounts conditions very similar to the associativity of the group <m>Q_8</m>).
                    </p>
    
                    <p>
                    <m>{\mathbb{H}}</m> is a division ring, since one can check that <me>(a + bi + cj + dk)^{-1} = \frac{a -  bi -  cj - dk}{\|a + bi + cj + dk\|}</me> where <me>\|a + bi + cj + dk \| := a^2 + b^2 + c^2 + d^2.</me>
                    </p>
    
                    <p>
                    In the equation above <m>\|a + bi + cj + dk \|</m> is non-zero real number if <m>a + bi + cj + dk</m> is not the zero element. The quantity <m>\|a + bi + cj + dk \|</m> is called the <em>norm</em> of the quaternion <m>a + bi + cj + dk</m>.
                    </p>
                    </li>
    
                    <li>
                            <p>
                    (<term>Direct product of rings</term>) The cartesian product <m>R\times R'</m> of two rings <m>R</m> and <m>R'</m> has a natural ring structure with addition and multiplication defined componentwise: <me>(a,b)+(c,d)=(a+c,b+d)</me> <me>(a,b)\cdot(c,d)=(a\cdot c,b\cdot d)</me>
                    </p>
                    </li>
    
                    <li>
                            <p>
                    If <m>X</m> is a set and <m>R</m> is a ring, let <m>\operatorname{Fun}(X, R)</m> be the collection of set theoretic functions from <m>X</m> to <m>R</m>, and define <m>(f + g)(x) = f(x) + g(x)</m> and <m>(f \cdot g)(x) := f(x) \cdot g(x)</m>. Then <m>\operatorname{Fun}(X,R)</m> is a ring. If <m>X</m> is a finite set and <m>|X|=n</m>, then <m>\operatorname{Fun}(X,R)</m> may be identified with <m>R^n=\underbrace{R \times \cdots \times R}_n</m>, the direct product of <m>n</m> copies of <m>R</m>.
                    </p>
                    </li>
    
                    <li>
                            <p>
                    (<term>Endomorphism ring</term>) If <m>A = (A, +)</m> is any abelian group, set <m>\operatorname{End}_{Ab}(A)</m> to be the collection of endomorphisms of <m>A</m> — that is, the set of group homomorphisms <m>f: A \to A</m> from <m>A</m> to itself.
                    </p>
    
                    <p>
                    Then <m>\operatorname{End}_{Ab}(A)</m> is a ring with addition <m>(f + g)(a) := f(a) + g(a)</m> and multiplication <m>f \cdot g := f \circ g</m>. This is almost always a non-commutative ring.
                    </p>
                    </li>
    
                    </ol></p>
                </example>
    
            </subsection>  
    
            <subsection xml:id="subsec-units">
                <title>Units, Zero Divisors, Integral Domains</title>
    
                <definition xml:id="def-unit">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                    An element <m>a</m> of a unital ring <m>R</m> with <m>1\neq 0</m> is called a <em>unit</em> there exists <m>b\in R</m> such that<m>ab=1</m> and <m>ba=1</m>. In case such <m>b</m> exists, it is unique, it is called the inverse of <m>a</m> and denoted by <m>a^{-1}</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                </definition>
    
                <definition xml:id="def-group-of-units">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                    The set of units of a non-trivial unital ring <m>R</m> is denoted <m>R^\times</m>. This forms a group <m>(R^\times,\cdot)</m> with respect to multiplication.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                </definition>
    
                <problem xml:id="exe-group-of-units-is-a-group">
                <p>
                    The group of units is indeed a group <m>(R^\times,\cdot)</m> with respect to multiplication.
                </p>
                </problem>
    
                <example xml:id="ex-matrices-and-units">
                <p>
                    <m>\operatorname{M}_{n}(F)^\times = \operatorname{GL}_n(F)</m>.
                </p>
                </example>
    
                <problem xml:id="exe-units-in-fields">
                    <p>
                        Let <m>F</m> be a field. Prove that every non-zero element of <m>F</m> is a unit. In symbols, show <m>F^\times=F\setminus\{0\}</m>.
                    </p>
                </problem>
    
                <definition xml:id="def-zero-divisor">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                    A <em>zero-divisor</em> in a ring <m>R</m> is an element <m>x\ne 0</m> such that <m>xy = 0</m> or <m>yx=0</m> for some <m>y \ne 0</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                </definition>
    
                <definition xml:id="def-integral-domain">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                    A unital ring <m>R</m> is an <em>integral domain</em> (often shortened to <em>domain</em>) if <m>1 \ne 0</m>, <m>R</m> is commutative, and <m>R</m> has no zero divisors.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                </definition>
    
                <lemma xml:id="lem-cancellation-in-integral-domains">
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>R</m> be a commutative ring with identity. Then <m>R</m> is an integral domain if and only if for all <m>x,y,z\in R</m> such that <m>xy=xz</m>, we have <m>y=z</m>. This property is called <alert>cancellation</alert>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                </lemma>
    
                <example xml:id="ex-integral-domains">
                    <p>
                        <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                            Every field is an integral domain.
                            </p>
                        </li>
        
                        <li>
                            <p>
                            <m>\Z/n</m> is an integral domain if and only if <m>n</m> is prime (in which case it happens to be a field too) or <m>n = 0</m> (in which case <m>\Z/0\cong \Z</m>).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </example>
    
                <problem xml:id="ex-finite-domains-fields">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Prove that a finite integral domain <m>D</m> must be a field.
                    </p>
                  </statement>
    
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>x\in D</m>, and consider the set <m>\{x^n|n\in\N\}</m>. As <m>D</m> is finite there must exist <m>n&lt;m\in\N</m> such that <m>x^n=x^m</m>. In integral domains cancellation is allowed, and thus we can cancel an <m>x^n</m> from both sides, yielding <m>e=x^{m-n}</m>, and thus <m>x\cdot x^{m-n-1}=e</m>, making <m>x</m> a unit of <m>D</m>. Thus <m>D</m> is a field.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </problem>
    
                <lemma xml:id="lem-zero-divisor-not-unit">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                    If <m>a</m> is a zero divisor in a ring <m>R</m>, then <m>a</m> is not a unit.
                    </p>
                </statement>
    
                <proof>
                    <p>
                    Suppose that <m>a</m> is both a zero divisor and a unit. Then there exists <m>b\neq 0</m> such that <m>ab=0</m> or <m>ba=0</m>. Multiplying either of these equations by <m>a^{-1}</m> gives <m>b=0</m>, a contradiction.
                    </p>
                </proof>
                </lemma>
    
                <problem xml:id="exe-neither-zero-divisor-nor-unit">
                  <p>
                    Give an example of a ring <m>R</m> and an element <m>a\in R</m> which is neither a unit nor a zero-divisor.
                  </p>
                </problem>
    
                <problem xml:id="exe-zero-divisor-or-unit-if-finite">
                  <p>
                    Prove that if <m>R</m> is finite then every element is either a unit of a zero-divisor.
                  </p>
                </problem>
    
                <definition xml:id="def-nilpotent">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                    An element <m>a</m> of a ring <m>R</m> is called <em>nilpotent</em> if <m>a^n = 0</m> for some integer <m>n \geq 1</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                </definition>
    
                <lemma xml:id="lem-nilpotents-and-units">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                    If <m>a</m> is a nilpotent element in a unital ring <m>R</m>, then <m>1-a</m> is a unit.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                </lemma>
    
                <problem xml:id="exe-one-plus-nilpotent-is-unit">
                <p>
                    Let <m>x</m> be a nilpotent element] of a ring. Show that <m>1 + x</m> is a unit of <m>A.</m> Deduce that the sum of a nilpotent element and a unit is a unit.
                </p>
                </problem>
    
                <definition xml:id="def-idempotent">
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Let <m>R</m> be a ring with identity. An element <m>e\in R</m> is called <em>idempotent</em> if <m>e^2=e</m>.
                    </p>
                  </statement>
                </definition>
    
                <problem>
                  <p>
                    Let <m>R</m> be a ring with identity.
    
                    <ol>
                      <li>
                        <p>
                          Give an example of a ring which has an idempotent other than <m>0</m> or <m>1</m>.
                        </p>
                      </li>
    
                      <li>
                        <p>
                          Prove that if <m>e</m> is idempotent, so is <m>1-e</m>.
                        </p>
                      </li>
    
                      <li>
                        <p>
                          Suppose <m>R</m> is commutative and <m>e</m> an idempotent. Let <m>Re:=\{re\mid r\in R\}</m>. Prove that <m>Re</m> is a commutative ring (with identity <m>e</m>).
                        </p>
                      </li>
                    </ol>
                  </p>
                </problem>
    
                <problem xml:id="exe-gaussian-units">
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Let <m>\Z[i] = \{a + bi \mid a,b \in \Z\}</m> be the ring of Gaussian integers. Define a function 
                    <me>
                      N:\Z[i]\to\Z, N(a+bi)=a^2+b^2.
                    </me>
    
                  
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        Prove that <m>N(\a\b)=N(\a)N(\b)</m> for any <m>\a,\b\in \Z[i]</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
    
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        Use the function <m>N</m> to determine the units of <m>\Z[i]</m>.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
    
                </p>
              </statement>
    
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    <ol>
                      <li>
                        <p>
                          Let <m>\alpha,\beta\in\Z[i]</m> and behold <m>\begin{align}N(\alpha\beta)&amp;=N((a+bi)(c+di))\\&amp;=N(ac-bd+adi+bci)\\&amp;=(ac-bd)^2+(ad+bc)^2\\&amp;=((ac)^2-2acbd+(bd)^2)+((ad)^2+2abcd+(bc^2))\\&amp;=a^2c^2+b^2d^2+a^2d^2+b^2c^2\\&amp;=(a^2c^2+a^2d^2)+(b^2c^2+b^2d^2)\\&amp;=a^2(c^2+d^2)+b^2(c^2+d^2)\\N(\alpha)N(\beta)&amp;=(a^2+b^2)(c^2+d^2).\end{align}</m> So there's that done.
                        </p>
                      </li>
    
                      <li>
                        <p>
                          Suppose <m>\alpha\beta=1</m>. Then by Part (a) we know 
                          <me>
                            N(\alpha)N(\beta)=N(\alpha\beta)=N(1)=1,
                          </me> 
                          so <m>(a^2+b^2)(c^2+d^2)=1</m>, with <m>a,b,c,d\in\Z</m>. Thus we have <m>a^2+b^2=1=c^2+d^2</m>. So the units of <m>\Z[i]</m> are <m>\{\pm 1,\pm i\}</m>.
                        </p>
                      </li>
                    </ol>
                  </p>
                </solution>
    
                </problem>
    
                <problem xml:id="exe-integral-hamiltonian-quaternions">
                  <p>
                    Let <m>S=\{a+bi+cj+dk \mid a,b,c,d \in \Z\}</m> be the ring of integral Hamiltonian quaternions, where multiplication is defined using the same rules as in <m>\mathbb{H}</m>. Define a function 
                    <me>
                      N:S\to\Z, N(a+bi+cj+dk)=a^2+b^2+c^2+d^2.
                    </me>
      
                    <ol>
                      <li>
                        <p>
                          For any <m>\a=a+bi+cj+dk\in S</m>, denote <m>\bar\a=a-bi-cj-dk</m>. Show that <m>\overline{\a\b}=\bar \b \bar\a</m> for all <m>\a,\b\in \mathbb{H}</m>.
                        </p>
                      </li>
      
                      <li>
                        <p>
                          Prove that <m>N(\a)=\a\bar\a</m> and <m>N(\a\b)=N(\a)N(\b)</m> for any <m>\a,\b\in S</m>.
                        </p>
                      </li>
      
                      <li>
                        <p>
                          Prove that <m>\a\in S^\times</m> if and only if <m>N(\a)=1</m>.
                        </p>
                      </li>
      
                      <li>
                        <p>
                          Show that there is a group isomorphism <m>(S^\times,\cdot)\cong Q_8</m>.
                        </p>
                      </li>
                    </ol>
                  </p>
                </problem>
    
    
            
            </subsection>
    
